{"/service/ndnp/idhi/batch_idhi_angelou_ver01/data/sn86091092/00295869409/1907112301/0990.xml":{"full_text":"zu\nENORMOUS REDUCTION:\nIn Table Linens at The Fair Store\nFROM NOW UNTIL THANKSGIVING\nThis coupled wlt\u00bbh the many bargains already offered in our GREAT DISSOLUTION SALE is\ngoing to make things interesting at our store and you'll BE THANKFUL if you visit us early.\nTHE PLACE TO SAVE MONEY.\nCALDWELL, IDAHO. H. B. AVEN, Proprietor.\n<\u00a3lje tribune\nCALDWELL, IDAHO\nfUBUSHED BY\nDAVIS BARNETT\nSubscription,\nf2.00 Per Annum\nWKKKI.Y ESTABLISHED DEC. 8, 1883\nami entered at thi' Catdwvll Postoftice as\nsecond-claas matter.\u2014Act of March 3, 1879\nADVERTISING RATES\nDisplay advertising. 17Xc inch per issue\nHeading notices, 10c per line.\nClassified advertisements, lc per word\nper issue.\nLEGAL NOTICE8\nFinal Proof Notices 7.60\nCon\u00eeest Notices,\u00bb 7.60\nNotice to Creditors 6.00\nN'it ice Proving Will 5.00\nAlius Summons 12.00\nAll other Legal Notices $1.00 per inch\n(solid nonpareil per issue tirst insertion\n60c per inch each subsequent insertion.\nThe Company will absolutely recognize\nno other prices, without contract, no matter\nby whom made.\nTHE COMMERCIAL CLUB.\nThe Caldwell Commercial Club Is\nengaged In a good work In advertis\ning Caldwell, Interesting people In\nthis locality, encouraging Immigra\ntion, and building up the country\naround us. We understand that the\nclub has inquiries from all over the\ncountry in regard to Caldwell. From\nPonce to Kamchatka the fame of the\nMagic City has spread. The people\nare coming hero for the purpose of\nlocating. They propose Investing\ntheir money In various ways. Some\nwant farms and orchards, some want\nto engage in business and some want\nto start various kinds of manufac\nturing enterprises. Others simply\nto safely Invest their money. Ail\nwho Inquire, are answered by the\nclub. They are given the Informa\ntion they desire and such other in\nformation as would be of general In\nterest. Literature is being sent out;\nand in fact everything Is being done\nto further the settlement of this part\nof the Btate. In this work the officers\nof the club should have the enthu\nsiastic co-operation and encourage\nment of all the people of Caldwell.\nThere are three ways of doing this:\nfirst, by paying your monthly dues;\nsecond, and more important, by at\ntending the regular weekly meetings;\nthird, and most important, by all re\nmembering and proclaiming that\nCaldwell Is the greatest town in the\nwest. Caldwell is the biggest town\nof its size in the world. It has every\nmodern improvement, such as street\ncars, electric lights, city water and\nsewerage. It has the finest and best\nbusiness houses in Idaho. It has\nthe most progressive people In the\nwest. It has the best schools and col\nleges. It has a climate that sur\npasses Italy; soil\u2014soil\u2014this was the\ngarden of Eden, years back, before\nthe advent of Tom Johnson and Wil\nliam Mosby. It has everything. Cald\nwell is the only town in Idaho of any\nconsequence, whose banks could\nweather a financial panic and never\nbat an eye. The Commercial Club\nis telling the people of our good for\ntune, of our great resources and of\nour assured greatness. The people\nshould lend the organisation every\nassistance in its power.\nSELF GOVERNMENT.\nThe idea seems to prevail that\nPresident Roosevelt might restore\n\u00bbTnfldence and prosperity simulta\nneously, by notifying the world In\ngeneral, and the United States In par\nticular, that he would accept the\nnomination for a third term. The\nsame persons also advance the argu\nment that the President, alone, can\nsafeguard the rights of the people\nand preserve individual liberty. The\nfirst idea is brought forth in the face\nof the fact that a great portion of\nthe people of the country actually be\nlieve that the present financial panic\nIs due directly to the radical and\nviolent velws; the spectacular meth\nods; and the indifferent attitude of\nthe President himself. These people\ncan argue with some reason. They\ncan point to the fact that the Presi\ndent has destroyed confidence In\nevery banker, financier, manufactur\ner and promoter in the country. He\nhas not hesitated to proclaim the fact\nthat all our big men are scoundrels\nand robbers and yet he expects peo\nple to have confidence. He must\nalso be spectacular in doing what he\ndoes. If a Chicago meat packing es\ntablishment is dirty, it should be pro\nclaimed from the house tops in order\nthat the industry may be destroyed.\nIf a pilot on the Mississippi is too\nspeedy he must be fired with blare\nof trumpets that the people may ap\npreciate the greatness of the Presi\ndent. His address at Nashville shows\nhis indifference. President Roose\nvelt's ethics must prevail, at no mat\nter what cost. If the people suffer It\nis their fault. Had they been up to\nhis standard, and in his financial\ncondition, a panic would not have in\njured them. As it is, he cannot help\nit. The wages of sin is death and\nthe sinner must die. We do not care\nmuch for the pro and cop of the\nfinancial panic. We do not believe\nthe President is solely responsible.\nBut there is another side to the ques\ntion that must gfve us pause. _If it\nhas come to this pass, when one man\nIs the Atlas upon whose shoulders\nrests the Untied States of America,\nthen the sooner we acknowledge the\nfailure of popular government the\nbetter. When 80,000,000 people\nbecome so senile that they can pro\nduce only one man capable of admln\nIstreing the government, it is high\ntime that we elect a hereditary king.\nWe think the people are simply suf\nfering from a temporary abearration\nof the mind. They have, for the time\nbeing, gone daffy. They are nuts In\ntheir hero-worship. But they will\nsoon reallie that they are free born;\nthat they have among them hundreds\nwho are capable of administering the\ngovernment. They will soon appre\nciate the fact that this government\nof, for and by the people will not\nperish from the earth upon the ex\npiration of President Roosevelt's\nterm of office. They will realise their\nown worth and dignity, and when\nthat realization dawns upon their\nminds they will know that crlilvea\nhave come and gone and we have\nnever lacked for men to guide the\ndestines of the nation. They will re\nalize that there are hundreds of men\nin the country who could pilot the\nship of state through any political\nchannel. There are Washingtons,\nLincolns, McKinleys and one or two\nRoosevelta in every hamlet In the\ncountry. The United States la no one\nhorse affair. The people are still ca\npable of Belf-government.\nFRENCH'S CANDIDACY.\nAbout the only sensible thing we\nhave seen in the Boise Unionist for\nseveral months past la the statement\nthat the labor unions should do well\nto support Representative Burton L.\nFrench In preferance to an unknown\nman. The Unionist, for once In Its\nlife. Is fair. It says that Mr. French\nIs fair and will give the labor unions\njust what Is coming to them\u2014no\nmore and no leu. The Tribune has\nlong known two or three things\nabout our representative in Congress.\nThese things are: first, Mr. French Is\nhonest and sincere. He will do as he\nthinks best without regard to the\neffect that it may have on himself.\nHe will stand by the unions so long\nas their demands are reasonable and\njust. He will stand against those\nunions when their cause Is unjust.\nHe has the courage of his convictions.\nThe union men of Idaho can expect\nno more from any man. Most of the\nunion men we have known have been\nvery good, patriotic, sensible Ameri\ncan citizens. They admire and re\nspect a man of courage and honesty.\nMr. French is a man of that kind.\nHe is also a man of ability. The\nhonest, sincere union men will make\nno mistake In supporting Burton L.\nFrench for Congress.\nKill the Dogs.\nA prominent citizen of Caldwell\ncalled the attention of The Tribune\nto the fact that many of our substan\ntial citizens are not paying the license\non their dogs. If a man must have\na dog he should be forced to pay well\nfor the privilege. Of all the unmiti\ngated nuisances abroad in the land,\nthe dog 1b the worst. He does no\ngood to anything except the fleas,\nwhich inhabit him. He produces\nnothing; breeds disease and incites\nriot. Those are the only uses he was\never known to have and none of them\nare of any general benefit. The\nwhole tribe should be banished the\ncity. They suck eggs, keep the\nneighborhood awake, and incite more\nblasphemy than all the cats in Christ\nendom, and heaven knows, they have\nsent more souls to hell than Calvin\nover damned. A man who seeks com\npanionship in a dog should pay for It.\nHe Is not entitled to any mercy. A\ndog Is a luxury and should be taxed\nto death. It is a selfish luxury. A\ndog is a dog and that is all there is\nto him. He has no virtues. He is\nincapable of doing good. It Is not\nthe dog's fault that he is a dog, but\nIt Is the city's fault if he Btays a dog\nlong. He should be killed on sight,\nbut if people must have dogs, make\nthem pay for the foolish habit. All\nother bad habits, except keeping a\ndog, are paid for here and hereafter\nand why not the dog habit? The\nWESTERN NATIONAL BANK\nCALDWELL, IDAHO\nCapital Stock, $50,000.oo\nSurplus Profits, 6,000.oo\nPROGRESSIVE COURTEOUS CONSERVATIVE\nOpened for Business June 2, 1906\nDEPOSITS OCTOBER L 1907 J275.000.00\nThe above deposits represent active live accounts. We ap\npreciate he efforts of oar friends and customers in helping\nas to make the above statement. Ask them why they have\nso freely assisted us ia building up oar business.\nU. S. DEPOSITORY\nOFFICERS:\nD D. CAMPBELL, President 8. D. 8IMP80N, Cashier\nJ. T. M0RRI80N, Vice-President J. K. RODDY, Asst. Cashier\nH. B. COSBY. Asst. Cashier\n5 Per Cent Paid on Time Deposits\nTribune urges the city administra\ntion to order all dogs killed and thus\nsecure the eternal gratitude of the\npeople of Caldwell. If this cannot be\ndone, make the owners of dogs pay\na good round license, say $100.00 per\nyear, but by all means make them\npay some license.\nTo Have New Theatre.\nNlelson Nichols, who own the\nunoccupied ground at Main and\nWashington streets, will at once be\ngin work on the foundations for a\ntwo-Btory building 4 5x138 feet next\nto the Steward building. The lower\nfloor will be arranged for business\npurposes, and the second story will\ncontain a splendidly equipped opera\nhouse.\nArrangements are now being made\nfor the excavation. A basement will\nbe constructed under the entire build\ning and this portion of the work will\nbe done this winter while the water\nis out of the ditches.\nThe opera house will be a modern\nplayhouse In every respect. It will\nhave ample stage and dressing rooms\nin the rear. A gallery will be placed\nin front.\u2014Emmett Index.\nPioneer Irrigation District Warrant\nCall.\nOn and after December 1st, 1907,\nI will pay Pioneer Irrigation District\nWarrants at my office In the First\nNational Bank, Caldwell, as follows:\nGeneral Fund, Nos. 1345 to 1389, Is\nsue of November 1, 1904; Mainte\nnance Fund, Nos. 379 to 417, issue\nof August 2, 1904.\nQ. D.SNELL, Jr., TreaB.\nF. O. E.\nAttention. Next regular meeting\npostponed to Friday evening, Nov\nember 29, 8 P. M. Important busi\nness. Something doing.\nH. H. COMPTON, W. S. .R\nMILK CONSUMERS' NOTICE.\nOn and after Nov. 15, 1907, on\naccount of the cost of labor and feed,\nthe price of milk will be raised from\n$1.50 per month for quarts to $3.00\nper month; pints from 76c to $1.25\nper month.\nV. A. COX,\nS. S. JUDD.\ntf Dairymen.\nSAY\nRemember If jam have am\nPLUMBING or TDOdMOto\ndo come and figan with m\nE. E. Harthrong\nGeneral Insurance Surety Bonds\nLIFE, FIRE, HEALTH, ACCIDENT, BURGLARY, PLATE\nGLASS INSURANCE AND ALL KINDS OF BONDS\n0 \u00f4. b B,d 8 b \"cA\u00b0Lo\u00c7;\u00ca^ CUPP CUPP WELKERSON\nQUESTION\u2014WhaL 's in a Name?\nANSWER\u2014It depends on the Name.\nTHE\nNAME\nSTUDEBAKER\nL\nstands, the world over, for SUPERIORITY in vehicle\nconstruction. This famous line comprises\nFarm Wagons, Mountain Hades, Fine Carriag\nes, Phaetons, Stanhopes, Driving Wagons, Run\nabouts, Two-Wheeled Vehicles, Buckboards,\nTop Buggies and Passenger Wagons of all de\nscriptions.\nQUALITY is first consideration\nPRJCE is reasonable\nIdaho Implement Co., k\u00cb\nCALDWELL, IDAHO\nTHERE are men who never send a\ntelegram without economizing ao closely\non the words that it is really uninteligible.\nThere are women who never buy coffee\nwithout economizing so closely on the\nprice that it is unappetiziug un stimulat\ning, and unsatisfying. Is this true economy\nRead the answer in a single trial pound\nof the finest grown coffee in the world,.\n\u2014Chase Sanborn's Seal Brand. Worth\na dollar a pound if yon like coffee.\nBallantyne Merc. Co.\nHardware and Groceries","height":"19896","width":"14160"}}
